import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/+$/, '');
---

<Base title="From a site-wide outage to the right metric — Andrew Yang">
  <p><a href={`${base}/work/`}>← Case studies</a></p>
  <span class="tag">performance</span>
  <h1>From a site-wide outage to the right metric</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    A production outage pointed at one service. Profiling cut its request load by
    84% — and then a service-time analysis showed that the obvious conclusion was
    wrong, and the real risks were two layers deeper.
  </p>

  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>
    The platform monitors thousands of solar plants. Every time new measurement
    data arrives, a calculation pipeline recomputes KPIs — availability,
    performance ratio, energy — for the affected system. The pipeline is
    queue-driven and runs continuously at roughly 150 calculation dispatches per
    second across the fleet.
  </p>

  <h2>Problem</h2>
  <p>
    A site-wide performance outage: the calculation pipeline generated enough
    traffic against the system-topology service to degrade the whole platform.
    A quick workaround (a cache in front of the hottest call) stopped the
    bleeding. I took the follow-up: find out what the pipeline was actually
    doing to its dependencies, and fix it structurally.
  </p>

  <h2>Measurement first</h2>
  <p>
    I surveyed the data flow of one calculation run — every module, every
    external source it touched — into a module-by-source matrix. Two findings
    stood out:
  </p>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      The dispatch stage made <strong>four uncached calls to the KPI
      configuration service per run</strong> — just to decide which modules to
      execute.
    </li>
    <li>
      The KPI configuration service was receiving <strong>925 requests per
      second, 100% of it from the calculation pipeline</strong>, almost all on a
      single config endpoint. Calculation delay had drifted to a median of ~9
      minutes against a ~5-minute baseline.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Design: resolve every input once</h2>
  <p>
    The structural fix was a per-run <strong>calculation context with data
    slots</strong>: each input a run needs — KPI configuration, device topology,
    measurement series — is resolved exactly once and shared by every module in
    that run, replacing fetch-as-you-go. Config lookups collapsed into one slot;
    the device-topology slot became shared by five modules.
  </p>
  <p>
    Result: KPI-config requests dropped from <strong>925 to 151 req/s — an 84%
    reduction in request count</strong> — and the hottest topology route roughly
    halved.
  </p>

  <h2>Then the correction</h2>
  <p>
    Here is the part I consider the real work. Before declaring victory I redid
    the analysis on a <strong>service-time axis</strong> (requests/s × latency)
    instead of request counts — and the conclusion changed:
  </p>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      The config endpoint averaged ~0.9 ms. 925 req/s of it is under one CPU
      core of work. <strong>The KPI service was never the load bottleneck</strong> —
      the −84% was a count reduction, not a load reduction.
    </li>
    <li>
      The genuine outage shape lived in the topology service: an endpoint at
      only ~28 req/s whose tail latency reached <strong>30 seconds</strong>,
      accounting for ~41% of that service's total service time.
    </li>
    <li>
      The dominant <em>compute</em> cost was elsewhere again: one module family
      accounted for <strong>52.6% of all calculation CPU</strong>, and 81–93% of
      its time was round-trips to the measurement-data API.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    So the honest value of the data-slot design is different from the headline
    number: it <strong>eliminated an unguarded-external-dependency outage
    class</strong> (the pipeline can no longer flood a dependency by design) and
    cut per-run wall-time by removing redundant round-trips. The follow-up
    priorities went to the 30-second tail and the compute-heavy module — where
    the service-time math said they belonged.
  </p>

  <h2>Impact</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>The outage class is gone: every external input is fetched once, behind a slot, per run.</li>
    <li>Hot-path request count −84%; hottest topology route ~−50%.</li>
    <li>
      My batch-prefetch proposal for the measurement-data round-trips was
      ultimately declined in favor of a deeper rework of that module family —
      built on the same measurements. The diagnosis was adopted; the remedy
      went further than my patch. That is how it should work.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What I'd tell my past self</h2>
  <p>
    Request count, service time, and compute are three different axes, and an
    outage only tells you which one screamed first. If I had shipped the slot
    design and stopped at "−84%", the 30-second tail would still be waiting for
    the next incident to make the point for me.
  </p>
</Base>
